          "body": "The first abuse is the most vivid in the chapter: Eliashib the priest had converted the temple's grain-offering storerooms into a private apartment for Tobiah the Ammonite — the very national identity that the law of 13:1 had just excluded. The political logic is transparent: Eliashib was related to Tobiah (13:4); family loyalty overrode covenantal obligation. Nehemiah's response is instantaneous and physical — 'I threw all of Tobiah's household goods out of the room' (13:8). The language is deliberately violent; the furniture of accommodation is ejected before a word of theological explanation is offered. The rooms are then ritually purified (taher) and the sacred supplies restored. The second discovery — that the Levites had not received their portions and had fled to their fields (13:10) — reveals the systemic consequence of the first: when the storeroom was profaned, the tithe-support system collapsed, and the entire apparatus of temple worship fell silent. Reform requires both purification of space and economic restoration of workers. Nehemiah closes the cycle with his first prayer: 'Remember me for this, O my God, and do not blot out my loyal deeds' (13:14). The Hebrew chesed — lovingkindness, covenant loyalty — is the word Nehemiah uses for his own acts; he frames his reform as an exercise of covenant faithfulness, not personal ambition."
