          "title": "Reform cycle three — mixed marriages and the Solomon comparison (13:23-31)",
          "body": "The third and most personally costly abuse is the most theologically freighted: Jews had married women from Ashdod, Ammon, and Moab (13:23) — precisely the nations excluded by the law of 13:1-2. The immediate visible consequence is linguistic: half the children of these marriages could not speak Hebrew (13:24). This is not merely a cultural loss; it is a covenant-transmission crisis. A generation that cannot speak the language of Torah cannot read the law that was just publicly read in verse 1. Nehemiah's confrontation is the most violent in the chapter — he curses, strikes, and pulls hair (13:25) — actions that modern readers find shocking but that reflect the gravity of the breach in ancient covenant culture. His theological argument is a case study from Israel's own royal history: Solomon, the wisest king, beloved of God, singled out by divine love and appointment, was drawn into sin by foreign women (13:26). The argument is a fortiori: if Solomon was not immune, you certainly are not. The most extreme case is reserved for last: a grandson of the high priest Eliashib had married a daughter of Sanballat the Horonite — Nehemiah's chief enemy throughout the book (2:10; 4:1; 6:1). The temple hierarchy and the opposition are now joined by marriage. Nehemiah drives him away (13:28). The final summary prayer (13:29-31) moves from imprecatory to petitionary: remember those who defiled the covenant of the priesthood (13:29) — and remember me for good (13:31). The book ends not in triumph but in bare trust: Nehemiah, having done everything a governor could do, hands the community's future to the God whose chesed alone can preserve what human hands cannot."
